  Just wanted to add 2 cents before anybody takes this name equivalence literally and goes on a wild goose chase.

  The arithmetic of one name being equivalent to 1000 other names are just phala shruti/artha-vada. Hence they are never meant to be taken literally ever. They are meant to encourage the devotee to pursue a particular path.

  1. The Rama Rameti shloka tells one Rama name equals 100 names of Vishnu. (This shloka is from Padma Purana)

  2. Next we have Brahmanda Purana that says:
  sahasra-namnam punyanam, trir-avrttya tu yat phalam;
  ekavrttya tu krsnasya, namaikam tat prayacchati

  one Krishna Japa = 3 Rama Japa

  3. What more, the same anushashasana parva in which Vishnu Sahasra Nama is present in Mahabharata has Krishna saying this :

  yO mAm nama sahasrena stotumicchati pandava
  yohamekena shlokena stuta eva na samshaya 

  By saying this Krishna is implying that one can get the same punya os saying entire Vishnu sahasra nama just by saying one shloka of Vishnu Sahasra nama.. Now each shloka of VSN is equivalent to entire VSN itself.. 
  Now we have circular reference in the equation that can never be satisfied !! (Much like GNU stands for GNU is not UNIX !!)

  Hence this one name being equivalent to N other names is a wild goose chase. As PVRji said, its all in the state of mind.

  But there is a specific meditation technique that can be specifically applied to Vishnu Sahasra nama and it is mentioned in preface of VSN itself (yaani naamaani gauNani vikhyaataani mahatmanah). Here gauNa does not mean minor. It means "being related to guna". It means each name extolls one (several actually) attributes of Vishnu. One can ponder over that quality of Vishnu as that name comes up. It takes up time to practice such technique and requires quite a bit of cross reference reading. It is to be slowly developed over time. But it is very effective.

  Regards,
  Srikanth

