  > There is no single "effective" way. Whether one is chanting oneself or 
  > listening to a person/cassette/CD/MP3, is not the primary factor. The 
  > primary factor is how focused one's mind is on it. The goal of chanting 
  > a stotra or a mantra is to eliminate or atleast limit other thoughts and 
  > focus the mind on it. That can happen with chanting as well as 
  > listening.
  > 
  > For example, I may be chanting Vishnu sahasra nama stotra and yet my 
  > mind may be wandering everywhere and focusing on all kind of dirty 
  > thoughts. Another person listening to me while doing some chores may be 
  > focusing a good part of their mental attention on the prayer and 
  > contemplating each word and its meaning and contemplating the qualities 
  > of Lord. In that case, that listener will get a lot more benefit from it 
  > than I will!
  > 
  > Each deity has some qualities. Focusing the mind on a deity and his/her 
  > mantra increases those qualities, over time, in one's own mind and in 
  > one's surroundings. If a lot of sadhakas with good concentration worship 
  > Chandi in this world, there may be a lot of violent outrage and fierce 
  > fight against adharma in this world. If a lot of sadhakas with good 
  > concentration worship Vishnu, there may be an upsurge of calm, 
  > self-assured and confident sattwa in the fight for establishing dharma. 
  > These energies balance each other. World is probably in a transition 
  > phase right now and worshippers of Chandi are needed. But, soon, we will 
  > need a lot more people worshipping Vishnu.
  > 
  > By the way, good sadhakas worshipping Ganesha increase the sense of 
  > stability and groundedness in the world.
  > 
  > Second: Anushtup is the metre with 8 syllables per line and 4 lines per 
  > verse. Whole Vishnu sahasra naama stotra is in anushtup metre. 
  > Traditionally, one specific verse is said to be equivalent to reading 
  > all 1000 names:
  > 
  > shrIrAma rAma rAmeti. rame rAme manorame.
  > sahasra nAma tattulyaM. rAma nAma vrAnane..
  > 
  > Actually, this verse means that chanting "shrIrAma rAma rAma" mantra 
  > (known as Amrita mantra) is equivalent to chanting 1000 names.
  > 
  > However, don't take it as a shortcut. If one is lazy and unfocused, 
  > chanting this verse even 100 times may do nothing. First, engage in some 
  > regular practices to remove laziness, instill discipline and sincerity, 
  > and get a state of mind where you can focus well on god. THEN the above 
  > 7-letter mantra can be as effective as 1000 names.
  > 
